                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-153311 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-child-abuse-and-neglect tag-domestic-service tag-education-k-12 tag-india des-child-abuse-and-neglect des-domestic-service des-education-k-12 geo-india" id="post-153311">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Lesson in Injustice</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Prajwal Parajuly			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-06-12T00:00:01+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 11, 2014 8:00 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 11, 2014 8:00 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I was 6, I saw my uncle slap, punch and kick the young boy who lived in his house. This wasn&#x2019;t unusual in the India of the early &#x2019;90s, and it isn&#x2019;t unusual even now. Parents routinely beat
                                        up kids, convinced that it is the best way to discipline them. A friend of mine in Gangtok, my hometown, came to school with stick marks tattooed on his arms every other week. This, though, was the first time that
                                        I had actually seen my uncle beating up a child. <span id="more-153311"></span></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The 8-year-old servant&#x2019;s crime? Allowing me to distract him from his chores. I had taken aside Ravi &#x2014; that was his name &#x2014; when he had nothing to do so I could teach him letters of the English alphabet.
                                        Ravi had never seen the inside of a classroom, but he was a quick learner. He held the pencil oddly, gripping it near the top at first &#x2014; perhaps because he had never used one before. He got confused about
                                        which direction &#x201C;B&#x201D; should face, and was amused by &#x201C;I&#x201D; &#x2014; disbelieving that a letter so simple would trail convoluted shapes like &#x201C;B&#x201D; and &#x201C;E.&#x201D; A single
                                        stick? He laughed, filling the notebook with two dozen I&#x2019;s. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was about to ask my pupil to draw an umbrella&#x2019;s handle, but before we could proceed to the delights of &#x201C;J,&#x201D; my uncle stormed in, accusation written all over his pink face. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was taken aback because I thought my uncle would be proud. Announcements promoting literacy were commonplace in India in those days. Often, advertisements on public television chided parents who refused their daughters
                                        the same education they gave their sons. Wasn&#x2019;t I doing my uncle a favor? </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ravi had been staying with my uncle and aunt for about a year at this point. My mother had procured him from an impoverished family living in her ancestral village in Nepal. My mother was a master of the art of servant
                                        hunting. Ever since she had moved to India from Nepal as a young bride, she regularly returned to her native village to pick out helpers for her middle-class friends and family. It&#x2019;s one fewer child starving
                                        to death, she&#x2019;d reason. Most other families in Gangtok employed indigenous servants from the India-Bhutan border, but my parents opted for Nepalese ones because they spoke our language. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sometimes I joined my mother on these trips. A hunt usually began with a surprise visit to a poor distant relative. The relative, a broker of sorts, would accompany us to several prospective servants&#x2019; houses.
                                        Terms and conditions of the income the servant would generate for his family were discussed: Yes, the parents would be given money every month; yes, the child would live with the employer&#x2019;s family and get
                                        an education if he behaved; yes, he would probably be allowed to visit home during important festivals; oh, yes, absolutely, he would get to eat the same food we ate. And the servant was handed over. Sometimes,
                                        there were tears. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ravi was supposed to be our servant, a replacement for the woman who had lived with us since before I was born but had left us in favor of her drunken husband. On the day he arrived, after my mother showed him where
                                        he&#x2019;d sleep, the areas of the house he wasn&#x2019;t allowed to trespass on, the plates and utensils that, as a servant, he couldn&#x2019;t touch, she realized there was a problem. The malnourished boy had
                                        head lice. My parents couldn&#x2019;t risk getting their school-attending children contaminated, so Ravi was temporarily transferred to my childless uncle&#x2019;s. There, he would be tonsured and deloused, before
                                        being shuttled back to our house. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But he never did come back. Our old servant decided that the beatings from her drunken husband had gotten to be too much, and she returned to us. Ravi remained at my uncle&#x2019;s. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He had a good life, my uncle and aunt told us. He was learning how to make tea, could wash dishes without supervision, and had enough youthful energy to sweep the floors of their four-story house twice a day from top
                                        to bottom. But they weren&#x2019;t about to send him to school anytime soon. It was a waste, Uncle said, while my mother looked away in guilt. He could always learn things at home. </p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/11/opinion/0611PRIVATELIVES/0611PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject"
                                            role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/11/opinion/0611PRIVATELIVES/0611PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/11/opinion/0611PRIVATELIVES/0611PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg"
                                                    id="100000002934035" width="480" height="480" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="480">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Connor Willumsen</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Which is why I thought Uncle&#x2019;s reaction to the little literary revolution I had engendered was so odd. The conversation that ensued when he discovered us went something like this: </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Don&#x2019;t you have any work to do?&#x201D; A punch landed on my student&#x2019;s face.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;It&#x2019;s finished,&#x201D; Ravi meekly replied. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Go wash the car then,&#x201D; Uncle thundered, with a quick, hard slap and a few kicks. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">His rage then turned to me.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;What were you doing with him?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Teaching him A-B-C-D.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Distracting him.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;He wasn&#x2019;t even working.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;How would you know that? He has a lot of work to do. And don&#x2019;t argue with me.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;You should treat him like he&#x2019;s a human being,&#x201D; I said, tearing up. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;If he&#x2019;s a human being, why don&#x2019;t you eat off the same plate he does?&#x201D; my uncle asked.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;He&#x2019;s not an animal,&#x201D; I said.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;If he&#x2019;s a human being, why don&#x2019;t you sleep in the same bed he does?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;You&#x2019;re mean.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;If he&#x2019;s a human being, why don&#x2019;t you wear the same clothes he does?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Well&#x2026;&#x201D; I offered, before slinking off. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;See, if he&#x2019;s a human being, eat from the same plate he does and sleep in the same bed he does,&#x201D; my uncle shouted. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Of course, I wasn&#x2019;t going to touch a servant&#x2019;s plate. It was vile, was what I had been told. Of course, I wasn&#x2019;t going to sleep in his bed. It probably housed fleas and bugs. This was what I had
                                        been taught. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even as a 6-year-old, I knew I was superior to Ravi and thousands of others like him. You didn&#x2019;t eat from the same plate a servant did &#x2014; even if the plate had been rinsed and scrubbed a dozen times &#x2014;
                                        because you&#x2019;d get sick. You&#x2019;d be contaminated by the servant&#x2019;s lowliness.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was master. Ravi was servant. And there were some things a master just didn&#x2019;t do. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Three weeks later, Ravi ran away. He stole a few hundred rupees from my aunt&#x2019;s wallet, some of my uncle&#x2019;s shoes, two plates and a cup. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Thefts are a casualty of servant keeping.&#x201D; My uncle shrugged as he made a note of the damage incurred. &#x201C;He&#x2019;s a survivor no doubt. I just hope he doesn&#x2019;t get killed.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No one reported the child&#x2019;s absence to the police.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ravi had left behind some of his clothes &#x2014; they were hand-me-downs from me even though he was bigger than I was &#x2014; and his notebook, filled out to the last page. The first nine letters of the alphabet had
                                        been repeated hundreds of times. The B&#x2019;s still faced the wrong direction. And I saw that Ravi had done what I used to do when I was troubled: I shaded in the half-circles of my B&#x2019;s, what I called the
                                        letter&#x2019;s &#x201C;balloons,&#x201D; with a variety of colors. Each and every one of Ravi&#x2019;s was also filled in, with drab gray. </p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/prajwal-parajuly">Prajwal Parajuly</a> is the author of the story collection &#x201C;The Gurkha&#x2019;s Daughter.&#x201D; </em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
